    "reasoning": "1. The module implements an 8x1 memory using an 8-bit shift register with D-type flip-flops. 2. The shift register shifts in the input 'S' on each positive edge of the clock when 'enable' is high. 3. The inputs A, B, C are used to select which of the 8 stored bits is output as Z. 4. Since A, B, C form a 3-bit address (ABC), we use them directly to index into the shift register. 5. An 8-to-1 multiplexer selects the appropriate Q bit based on ABC values. 6. To avoid syntax error, all signals are declared as 'logic'. 7. The module uses proper sequential logic with 'always @(posedge clk)' and combinational logic with 'always @(*)'. 8. No 'unique' or 'inside' keywords are used. 9. The module is structured to meet exactly the interface specified.",
    "module": "module TopModule (\n    input clk,\n    input enable,\n    input S,\n    input A,\n    input B,\n    input C,\n    output Z\n);\n\n    // 8-bit shift register\n    logic [7:0] q;\n\n    // Shift register input\n    always @(posedge clk) begin\n        if (enable)\n            q <= {S, q[7:1]};\n    end\n\n    // 8-to-1 multiplexer to select output based on ABC\n    always @(*) begin\n        case ({A, B, C})\n            3'b000: Z = q[0];\n            3'b001: Z = q[1];\n            3'b010: Z = q[2];\n            3'b011: Z = q[3];\n            3'b100: Z = q[4];\n            3'b101: Z = q[5];\n            3'b110: Z = q[6];\n            3'b111: Z = q[7];\n            default: Z = 1'bx;\n        endcase\n    end\n\nendmodule"
}
